ing Work offers a powerful new framework for understanding women&apos;s work in a holistic sense, acknowledging both their responsibilities in supporting others as well as their employment duties.Beyond Caring Labour to Provisioning Work is based on a four-year, multi-site study of women who are members of contemporary community organizations. The authors reveal the complex ways in which these women define and value their own work, investigating what supports and constrains their individual and collective efforts. Calling on the state to assist more with citizens&apos; provisioning responsibilities, Beyond Caring Labour to Provisioning Work provides an excellent basis for new discussions on equitable and sustainable public policies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPoor womenxEmploymentzCanada. 0aPoor womenzCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aPoor womenzCanada. 0aWomen in community developmentzCanada. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBaker-Collins, Stephanie , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCerny, Judy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReitsma-Street, Marge, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aReitsma-Street, Marge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTam, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269572640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442695726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442695726.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK